postcontent: Winchester repeating arms model 1873 serial #71495 manufacture date 1881 The Model 1873 was one of the most successful Winchester rifles of its day, gaining the reputation as "The Gun that Won the West". Still an icon almost a century and a half later, it was manufactured between 1873 and 1919. Originally chambered for the .44-40 cartridge, it was later produced in .38-40 and .32-20, all of which were also popular handgun cartridges of the day, allowing users to conveniently carry just one type of ammunition. The Model 1873 was produced in three variations: a 24" barrel rifle, 20" barrel carbine, and a musket. The Model 1897 was an evolution of the Winchester Model 1893 designed by John Browning. From 1897 until 1957, over one million of these shotguns were produced. The Model 1897 was offered in numerous barrel lengths and grades, chambered in 12 and 16 gauge, and as a solid frame or takedown. Special length barrels could be ordered in lengths as short as 20 inches, and as long as 36 inches. title: For Sale:  Colt” Single Action Army .38
postcontent: Text me at (724) 471-8431 for more detailsThis Colt Single Action Army revolver in .38 special has a 5 ½” blued barrel with a color-case hardened frame and one piece, presentation grade ivory grips. This is one of the most sought after SAA models because the .38 Special chambering was discontinued from the line in 1964. Colt SAA revolvers made in 1956 are also more desirable because it was the first year of second generation production and the hand-fit quality was the best. Colt made a total of 2,706 revolvers in .38 Special with 5 ½” barrels that year.Positive proof that this is an original from 1956 is the low serial number (in the 5000SA range), plus the 3 digit assembly number, on the face of the cylinder, the loading gate and the rear of the frame. The revolver has a shiny bore and chambers, gently aged case colors and bright polished bluing on the barrel and cylinder. There are light scratches on the cylinder and minor bluing wear on the leading edge.
